<h1>@HI{{ya}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong> ... 
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong> @HI{{ina}} <strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong> is used to join nouns in a non-exhaustive list. Its use implies that the nouns
listed are some examples taken from a larger list. In this usage <strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong> is
often combined with <a href="grammar-particle-nado.html">@HI{{nado}}</a>. Compare <strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong> 
with <a href="grammar-particle-to.html">@HI{{to}}</a>, which can be used to provide an exhaustive listing
of nouns.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{te-buru}}no@KJ{{above}}ni,osushi<strong>ya</strong>yakitori<strong>ya</strong>
tenpuranadogaarimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      On the table there are such things as sushi, yakitori and tempura.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The idomatic expression <strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong> @HI{{ina}} <strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong>
means "as soon as" or "no sooner had".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ofuroni@KJ{{enter}}ru<strong>ya</strong> @HI{{ina}} <strong>ya</strong>,
      @KJ{{electricity^tale}}ga@KJ{{chirp}}tta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No sooner had I gotten into the bath than the telephone rang.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong> cannot be used to combine predicates, only nouns or noun phrases.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ya}}</strong> inexhaustively lists items that are related to a specific time and place, whereas
<a href="grammar-particle-toka.html">@HI{{toka}}</a> inexhaustively lists items in a more general fashion.
</p>

